In Mac:

Open Terminal:

kill -9 $(lsof -t -i:8080)





To instantly kill whatever is running on port 8080 on your Mac, open your Terminal and run this one-line command: [1, 2, 3]

kill -9 $(lsof -t -i:8080)


If you prefer to see what is running first or want alternative methods, follow the broken-down steps below. 
Option 1: The Step-by-Step Way (Recommended)
This method lets you check what application is using the port before you force-close it.
1.	Find the Process ID (PID): Open Terminal and run the following command:

lsof -i :8080

2.	Identify the PID: Look at the output table. Locate the number listed under the PID column.

3.	Kill the process: Run the kill command by replacing YOUR_PID with that number:

kill -9 YOUR_PID



Option 2: Using Node/NPX (Easiest for Web Developers)
If you are a web developer and have Node.js installed, you can use the built-in kill-port package without needing to look up PIDs: [1]

npx kill-port 8080



Option 3: Troubleshooting Permission Issues
If you get a permission error or the process refuses to close, elevate your terminal privileges with sudo: 

sudo kill -9 $(sudo lsof -t -i:8080)

(Note: You will be prompted to type your Mac's login password).




